[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Data provenance or data lineage can be used to make the debugging of Big Data pipeline easier.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This necessitates the collection of data about data transformations.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The below section will explain data provenance in more detail.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] In information systems, **data provenance** is information about the entities, activities, and agents involved in producing a piece of data; it records how data was derived and can be used to assess quality, reliability, and trustworthiness.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Classical database research distinguishes **why**, **where**, and **how** provenance and shows how these forms support tasks such as query debugging, view maintenance, confidence estimation, and annotation propagation.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] In scientific workflows, provenance documents the derivation history from original sources through workflow steps, supporting reproducibility and reuse of results.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Open, implementation-oriented specifications such as **OpenLineage** model lineage in terms of jobs, runs, and datasets to enable automated capture from modern data pipelines.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Provenance is information about entities, activities and people involved in producing a piece of data or thing, which can be used to form assessments about its quality, reliability or trustworthiness.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] is defined as a record that describes the people, institutions, entities and activities involved in producing, influencing, or delivering a piece of data or something.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] In particular, the provenance of information is crucial in deciding whether information is to be trusted, how it should be integrated with other diverse information sources, and how to give credit to its originators when reusing it.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] In an open and inclusive environment such as the Web, where users find information that is often contradictory or questionable, provenance can help those users to make trust judgements.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Intuitively, for an operator T producing output o , lineage consists of triplets of form $\{i,T,o\}$ , where i is the set of inputs to T used to derive o .
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] A query that finds the inputs deriving an output is called a *backward tracing query*, while one that finds the outputs produced by an input is called a *forward tracing query*.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Backward tracing is useful for debugging, while forward tracing is useful for tracking error propagation.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Tracing queries also form the basis for replaying an original dataflow.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] However, to efficiently use lineage in a DISC system, we need to be able to capture lineage at multiple levels (or granularities) of operators and data, capture accurate lineage for DISC processing constructs and be able to trace through multiple dataflow stages efficiently.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] A DISC system consists of several levels of operators and data, and different use cases of lineage can dictate the level at which lineage needs to be captured.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Lineage can be captured at the level of the job, using files and giving lineage tuples of form {IF i, M RJob, OF i }, lineage can also be captured at the level of each task, using records and giving, for example, lineage tuples of form {(k rr, v rr ), map, (k m, v m )}.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The first form of lineage is called coarse-grain lineage, while the second form is called fine-grain lineage.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Integrating lineage across different granularities enables users to ask questions such as "Which file read by a MapReduce job produced this particular output record?" and can be useful in debugging across different operators and data granularities within a dataflow.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] To capture end-to-end lineage in a DISC system, we use the Ibis model, which introduces the notion of containment hierarchies for operators and data.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Specifically, Ibis proposes that an operator can be contained within another and such a relationship between two operators is called *operator containment*.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Operator containment implies that the contained (or child) operator performs a part of the logical operation of the containing (or parent) operator.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] For example, a MapReduce task is contained in a job.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Similar containment relationships exist for data as well, Known as data containment.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Data containment implies that the contained data is a subset of the containing data (superset).
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Data lineage systems can be categorized as either eager or lazy.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Eager collection systems capture the entire lineage of the data flow at run time.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The kind of lineage they capture may be coarse-grain or fine-grain, but they do not require any further computations on the data flow after its execution.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Lazy lineage collection typically captures only coarse-grain lineage at run time.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] These systems incur low capture overheads due to the small amount of lineage they capture.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] However, to answer fine-grain tracing queries, they must replay the data flow on all (or a large part) of its input and collect fine-grain lineage during the replay.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This approach is suitable for forensic systems, where a user wants to debug an observed bad output.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Eager fine-grain lineage collection systems incur higher capture overheads than lazy collection systems.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] However, they enable sophisticated replay and debugging.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] An actor is an entity that transforms data; it may be a Dryad vertex, individual map and reduce operators, a MapReduce job, or an entire dataflow pipeline.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Actors act as black boxes and the inputs and outputs of an actor are tapped to capture lineage in the form of associations, where an association is a triplet $\{i,T,o\}$ that relates an input i with an output o for an actor T .
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The instrumentation thus captures lineage in a dataflow one actor at a time, piecing it into a set of associations for each actor.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The system developer needs to capture the data an actor reads (from other actors) and the data an actor writes (to other actors).
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] For example, a developer can treat the Hadoop Job Tracker as an actor by recording the set of files read and written by each job.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Association is a combination of the inputs, outputs and the operation itself.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The operation is represented in terms of a black box also known as the actor.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The associations describe the transformations that are applied to the data.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The associations are stored in the association tables.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Each unique actor is represented by its association table.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] An association itself looks like {i, T, o} where i is the set of inputs to the actor T and o is the set of outputs produced by the actor.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Associations are the basic units of Data Lineage.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Individual associations are later clubbed together to construct the entire history of transformations that were applied to the data.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Big data systems increase capacity by adding new hardware or software entities into the distributed system.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This process is called *horizontal scaling*.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The distributed system acts as a single entity at the logical level even though it comprises multiple hardware and software entities.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The system should continue to maintain this property after horizontal scaling.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] An important advantage of horizontal scalability is that it can provide the ability to increase capacity on the fly.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The biggest plus point is that horizontal scaling can be done using commodity hardware.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The horizontal scaling feature of Big Data systems should be taken into account while creating the architecture of lineage store.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This is essential because the lineage store itself should also be able to scale in parallel with the Big Data system.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The number of associations and amount of storage required to store lineage will increase with the increase in size and capacity of the system.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The architecture of Big Data systems makes use of a single lineage store not appropriate and impossible to scale.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The immediate solution to this problem is to distribute the lineage store itself.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The best-case scenario is to use a local lineage store for every machine in the distributed system network.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This allows the lineage store also to scale horizontally.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] In this design, the lineage of data transformations applied to the data on a particular machine is stored on the local lineage store of that specific machine.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The lineage store typically stores association tables.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Each actor is represented by its own association table.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The rows are the associations themselves, and the columns represent inputs and outputs.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] It allows horizontal scaling of the lineage store.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] If a single centralized lineage store was used, then this information had to be carried over the network, which would cause additional network latency.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The network latency is also avoided by the use of a distributed lineage store.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The information stored in terms of associations needs to be combined by some means to get the data flow of a particular job.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] In a distributed system a job is broken down into multiple tasks.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] One or more instances run a particular task.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The results produced on these individual machines are later combined to finish the job.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Tasks running on different machines perform multiple transformations on the data in the machine.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] All the transformations applied to the data on a machine is stored in the local lineage store of that machines.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This information needs to be combined to get the lineage of the entire job.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The lineage of the entire job should help the data scientist understand the data flow of the job and he/she can use the data flow to debug the Big Data pipeline.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The data flow is reconstructed in 3 stages.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The first stage of the data flow reconstruction is the computation of the association tables.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The association tables exist for each actor in each local lineage store.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The entire association table for an actor can be computed by combining these individual association tables.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This is generally done using a series of equality joins based on the actors themselves.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] In few scenarios the tables might also be joined using inputs as the key.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Indexes can also be used to improve the efficiency of a join.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The joined tables need to be stored on a single instance or a machine to further continue processing.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] There are multiple schemes that are used to pick a machine where a join would be computed.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The easiest one being the one with minimum CPU load.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Space constraints should also be kept in mind while picking the instance where join would happen.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The second step in data flow reconstruction is computing an association graph from the lineage information.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The graph represents the steps in the data flow.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The actors act as vertices and the associations act as edges.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Each actor T is linked to its upstream and downstream actors in the data flow.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] An upstream actor of T is one that produced the input of T, while a downstream actor is one that consumes the output of T.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Containment relationships are always considered while creating the links.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The graph consists of three types of links or edges.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The simplest link is an explicitly specified link between two actors.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] These links are explicitly specified in the code of a machine learning algorithm.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] When an actor is aware of its exact upstream or downstream actor, it can communicate this information to lineage API.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This information is later used to link these actors during the tracing query.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] For example, in the MapReduce architecture, each map instance knows the exact record reader instance whose output it consumes.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Developers can attach data flow archetypes to each logical actor.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] A data flow archetype explains how the child types of an actor type arrange themselves in a data flow.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] With the help of this information, one can infer a link between each actor of a source type and a destination type.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] For example, in the MapReduce architecture, the map actor type is the source for reduce, and vice versa.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The system infers this from the data flow archetypes and duly links map instances with reduce instances.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] However, there may be several MapReduce jobs in the data flow and linking all map instances with all reduce instances can create false links.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] To prevent this, such links are restricted to actor instances contained within a common actor instance of a containing (or parent) actor type.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Thus, map and reduce instances are only linked to each other if they belong to the same job.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] In distributed systems, sometimes there are implicit links, which are not specified during execution.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] For example, an implicit link exists between an actor that wrote to a file and another actor that read from it.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Such links connect actors which use a common data set for execution.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The dataset is the output of the first actor and the input of the actor follows it.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The final step in the data flow reconstruction is the topological sorting of the association graph.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The directed graph created in the previous step is topologically sorted to obtain the order in which the actors have modified the data.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This record of modifications by the different actors involved is used to track the data flow of the Big Data pipeline or task.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This is the most crucial step in Big Data debugging.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The captured lineage is combined and processed to obtain the data flow of the pipeline.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The data flow helps the data scientist or a developer to look deeply into the actors and their transformations.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This step allows the data scientist to figure out the part of the algorithm that is generating the unexpected output.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] A Big Data pipeline can go wrong in two broad ways.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The first is a presence of a suspicious actor in the dataflow.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The second is the existence of outliers in the data.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The first case can be debugged by tracing the dataflow.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] By using lineage and data-flow information together a data scientist can figure out how the inputs are converted into outputs.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] During the process actors that behave unexpectedly can be caught.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Either these actors can be removed from the data flow, or they can be augmented by new actors to change the dataflow.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The improved dataflow can be replayed to test the validity of it.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Debugging faulty actors include recursively performing coarse-grain replay on actors in the dataflow, which can be expensive in resources for long dataflows.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Another approach is to manually inspect lineage logs to find anomalies, which can be tedious and time-consuming across several stages of a dataflow.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Furthermore, these approaches work only when the data scientist can discover bad outputs.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] To debug analytics without known bad outputs, the data scientist needs to analyze the dataflow for suspicious behavior in general.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] However, often, a user may not know the expected normal behavior and cannot specify predicates.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This section describes a debugging methodology for retrospectively analyzing lineage to identify faulty actors in a multi-stage dataflow.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] We believe that sudden changes in an actor's behavior, such as its average selectivity, processing rate or output size, is characteristic of an anomaly.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Lineage can reflect such changes in actor behavior over time and across different actor instances.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Thus, mining lineage to identify such changes can be useful in debugging faulty actors in a dataflow.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The second problem i.e. the existence of outliers can also be identified by running the dataflow step wise and looking at the transformed outputs.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The data scientist finds a subset of outputs that are not in accordance with the rest of outputs.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The inputs which are causing these bad outputs are outliers in the data.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This problem can be solved by removing the set of outliers from the data and replaying the entire dataflow.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] It can also be solved by modifying the machine learning algorithm by adding, removing or moving actors in the dataflow.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The changes in the dataflow are successful if the replayed dataflow does not produce bad outputs.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Although the utilization of data lineage methodologies represents a novel approach to the debugging of Big Data pipelines, the process is not straightforward.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] A number of challenges must be addressed, including the scalability of the lineage store, the fault tolerance of the lineage store, the accurate capture of lineage for black box operators, and numerous other considerations.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] These challenges must be carefully evaluated in order to develop a realistic design for data lineage capture, taking into account the inherent trade-offs between them.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] DISC systems are primarily batch processing systems designed for high throughput.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] They execute several jobs per analytics, with several tasks per job.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The overall number of operators executing at any time in a cluster can range from hundreds to thousands depending on the cluster size.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Lineage capture for these systems must be able scale to both large volumes of data and numerous operators to avoid being a bottleneck for the DISC analytics.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Lineage capture systems must also be fault tolerant to avoid rerunning data flows to capture lineage.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] At the same time, they must also accommodate failures in the DISC system.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] To do so, they must be able to identify a failed DISC task and avoid storing duplicate copies of lineage between the partial lineage generated by the failed task and duplicate lineage produced by the restarted task.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] A lineage system should also be able to gracefully handle multiple instances of local lineage systems going down.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This can be achieved by storing replicas of lineage associations in multiple machines.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] The replica can act like a backup in the event of the real copy being lost.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Lineage systems for DISC dataflows must be able to capture accurate lineage across black-box operators to enable fine-grain debugging.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Although producing highly accurate lineage, such techniques can incur significant time overheads for capture or tracing, and it may be preferable to instead trade some accuracy for better performance.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Thus, there is a need for a lineage collection system for DISC dataflows that can capture lineage from arbitrary operators with reasonable accuracy, and without significant overheads in capture or tracing.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Tracing is essential for debugging, during which a user can issue multiple tracing queries.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Thus, it is important that tracing has fast turnaround times.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Ikeda et al. can perform efficient backward tracing queries for MapReduce dataflows but are not generic to different DISC systems and do not perform efficient forward queries.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Lipstick, a lineage system for Pig, while able to perform both backward and forward tracing, is specific to Pig and SQL operators and can only perform coarse-grain tracing for black-box operators.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Thus, there is a need for a lineage system that enables efficient forward and backward tracing for generic DISC systems and dataflows with black-box operators.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Replaying only specific inputs or portions of dataflow is crucial for efficient debugging and simulating what-if scenarios.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Ikeda et al. present a methodology for a lineage-based refresh, which selectively replays updated inputs to recompute affected outputs.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] This is useful during debugging for re-computing outputs when a bad input has been fixed.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] However, sometimes a user may want to remove the bad input and replay the lineage of outputs previously affected by the error to produce error-free outputs.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Another use of replay in debugging involves replaying bad inputs for stepwise debugging (called selective replay).
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Current approaches to using lineage in DISC systems do not address these.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Thus, there is a need for a lineage system that can perform both exclusive and selective replays to address different debugging needs.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] One of the primary debugging concerns in DISC systems is identifying faulty operators.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] In long dataflows with several hundreds of operators or tasks, manual inspection can be tedious and prohibitive.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] Even if lineage is used to narrow the subset of operators to examine, the lineage of a single output can still span several operators.
[src:apache-nifi/data-lineage] There is a need for an inexpensive automated debugging system, which can substantially narrow the set of potentially faulty operators, with reasonable accuracy, to minimize the amount of manual examination required.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] In computer programming, **dataflow programming** is a programming paradigm that models a program as a directed graph of the data flowing between operations, thus implementing dataflow principles and architecture.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programming languages share some features of functional languages, and were generally developed in order to bring some functional concepts to a language more suitable for numeric processing.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Some authors use the term *datastream* instead of *dataflow* to avoid confusion with dataflow computing or dataflow architecture, based on an indeterministic machine paradigm.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programming was pioneered by Jack Dennis and his graduate students at MIT in the 1960s.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Traditionally, a program is modelled as a series of operations happening in a specific order; this may be referred to as sequential, procedural, control flow (indicating that the program chooses a specific path), or imperative programming.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] The program focuses on commands, in line with the von Neumann vision of sequential programming, where data is normally "at rest".
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] In contrast, dataflow programming emphasizes the movement of data and models programs as a series of connections.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Explicitly defined inputs and outputs connect operations, which function like black boxes.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] An operation runs as soon as all of its inputs become valid.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Thus, dataflow languages are inherently parallel and can work well in large, decentralized systems.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] One of the key concepts in computer programming is the idea of state, essentially a snapshot of various conditions in the system.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Most programming languages require a considerable amount of state information, which is generally hidden from the programmer.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Often, the computer itself has no idea which piece of information encodes the enduring state.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] This is a serious problem, as the state information needs to be shared across multiple processors in parallel processing machines.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Most languages force the programmer to add extra code to indicate which data and parts of the code are important to the state.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] This code tends to be both expensive in terms of performance, as well as difficult to read or debug.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Explicit parallelism is one of the main reasons for the poor performance of Enterprise Java Beans when building data-intensive, non-OLTP applications.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Where a sequential program can be imagined as a single worker moving between tasks (operations), a dataflow program is more like a series of workers on an assembly line, each doing a specific task whenever materials are available.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Since the operations are only concerned with the availability of data inputs, they have no hidden state to track, and are all "ready" at the same time.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programs are represented in different ways.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] A traditional program is usually represented as a series of text instructions, which is reasonable for describing a serial system which pipes data between small, single-purpose tools that receive, process, and return.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programs start with an input, perhaps the command line parameters, and illustrate how that data is used and modified.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] The flow of data is explicit, often visually illustrated as a line or pipe.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] In terms of encoding, a dataflow program might be implemented as a hash table, with uniquely identified inputs as the keys, used to look up pointers to the instructions.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] When any operation completes, the program scans down the list of operations until it finds the first operation where all inputs are currently valid, and runs it.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] When that operation finishes, it will typically output data, thereby making another operation become valid.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] For parallel operation, only the list needs to be shared; it is the state of the entire program.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Thus the task of maintaining state is removed from the programmer and given to the language's runtime.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] On machines with a single processor core where an implementation designed for parallel operation would simply introduce overhead, this overhead can be removed completely by using a different runtime.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Some recent dataflow libraries such as Differential/Timely Dataflow have used incremental computing for much more efficient data processing.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] A pioneer dataflow language was BLOck DIagram (BLODI), published in 1961 by John Larry Kelly, Jr., Carol Lochbaum and Victor A.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Vyssotsky for specifying sampled data systems.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] A BLODI specification of functional units (amplifiers, adders, delay lines, etc.) and their interconnections was compiled into a single loop that updated the entire system for one clock tick.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] In a 1966 Ph.D. thesis, *The On-line Graphical Specification of Computer Procedures*, Bert Sutherland created one of the first graphical dataflow programming frameworks in order to make parallel programming easier.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Subsequent dataflow languages were often developed at the large supercomputer labs.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] SISAL, a popular dataflow language developed at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, looks like most statement-driven languages, but variables should be assigned once.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] This allows the compiler to easily identify the inputs and outputs.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] A number of offshoots of SISAL have been developed, including SAC, *Single Assignment C*, which tries to remain as close to the popular C programming language as possible.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] The United States Navy funded development of signal processing graph notation (SPGN) and ACOS starting in the early 1980s.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] This is in use on a number of platforms in the field today.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] A more radical concept is Prograph, in which programs are constructed as graphs onscreen, and variables are replaced entirely with lines linking inputs to outputs.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] Prograph was originally written on the Macintosh, which remained single-processor until the introduction of the DayStar Genesis MP in 1996.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] There are many hardware architectures oriented toward the efficient implementation of dataflow programming models.
[src:apache-nifi/dataflow-programming] MIT's tagged token dataflow architecture was designed by Greg Papadopoulos.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] A properly designed ETL system extracts data from source systems and enforces data type and data validity standards and ensures it conforms structurally to the requirements of the output.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems can also deliver data in a presentation-ready format so that application developers can build applications and end users can make decisions.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] The ETL process is often used in data warehousing.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] ETL systems commonly integrate data from multiple applications (systems), typically developed and supported by different vendors or hosted on separate computer hardware.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] The separate systems containing the original data are frequently managed and operated by different stakeholders.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] For example, a cost accounting system may combine data from payroll, sales, and purchasing.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] ETL and its variant ELT (extract, load, transform), are increasingly used in cloud-based data warehousing.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Applications involve not only batch processing, but also real-time streaming.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] ETL processing involves extracting the data from the source system(s).
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] In many cases, this represents the most important aspect of ETL, since extracting data correctly sets the stage for the success of subsequent processes.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Most data-warehousing projects combine data from different source systems.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Each separate system may also use a different data organization and/or format.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] The streaming of the extracted data source and loading on-the-fly to the destination database is another way of performing ETL when no intermediate data storage is required.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] An intrinsic part of the extraction involves data validation to confirm whether the data pulled from the sources has the correct/expected values in a given domain (such as a pattern/default or list of values).
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] If the data fails the validation rules, it is rejected entirely or in part.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] The rejected data is ideally reported back to the source system for further analysis to identify and to rectify incorrect records or perform data wrangling.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] In the data transformation stage, a series of rules or functions are applied to the extracted data in order to prepare it for loading into the end target.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] An important function of transformation is data cleansing, which aims to pass only "proper" data to the target.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] The challenge when different systems interact is in the relevant systems' interfacing and communicating.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Character sets that may be available in one system may not be in others.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] The load phase loads the data into the end target, which can be any data store including a simple delimited flat file or a data warehouse.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Depending on the requirements of the organization, this process varies widely.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Some data warehouses may overwrite existing information with cumulative information; updating extracted data is frequently done on a daily, weekly, or monthly basis.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Other data warehouses (or even other parts of the same data warehouse) may add new data in a historical form at regular intervals – for example, hourly.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] To understand this, consider a data warehouse that is required to maintain sales records of the last year.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] This data warehouse overwrites any data older than a year with newer data.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] However, the entry of data for any one year window is made in a historical manner.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] The timing and scope to replace or append are strategic design choices dependent on the time available and the business needs.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] More complex systems can maintain a history and audit trail of all changes to the data loaded in the data warehouse.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] As the load phase interacts with a database, the constraints defined in the database schema – as well as in triggers activated upon data load – apply (for example, uniqueness, referential integrity, mandatory fields), which also contribute to the overall data quality performance of the ETL process.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Audit reports (for example, on compliance with business rules.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Archive (Extreme, space-efficient compression for very rarely used, old data.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] ETL processes can involve considerable complexity, and significant operational problems can occur with improperly designed ETL systems.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] The range of data values or data quality in an operational system may exceed the expectations of designers at the time validation and transformation rules are specified.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Data profiling of a source during data analysis can identify the data conditions that must be managed by transform rules specifications, leading to an amendment of validation rules explicitly and implicitly implemented in the ETL process.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Data warehouses are typically assembled from a variety of data sources with different formats and purposes.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] As such, ETL is a key process to bring all the data together in a standard, homogeneous environment.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Design analysis should establish the scalability of an ETL system across the lifetime of its usage – including understanding the volumes of data that must be processed within service level agreements.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] The time available to extract from source systems may change, which may mean the same amount of data may have to be processed in less time.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems have to scale to process terabytes of data to update data warehouses with tens of terabytes of data.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Increasing volumes of data may require designs that can scale from daily batch to multiple-day micro batch to integration with message queues or real-time change-data-capture for continuous transformation and update.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Unique keys play an important part in all relational databases, as they tie everything together.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] A unique key is a column that identifies a given entity, whereas a foreign key is a column in another table that refers to a primary key.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Keys can comprise several columns, in which case they are composite keys.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] In many cases, the primary key is an auto-generated integer that has no meaning for the business entity being represented, but solely exists for the purpose of the relational database – commonly referred to as a surrogate key.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] As there is usually more than one data source getting loaded into the warehouse, the keys are an important concern to be addressed.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] For example: customers might be represented in several data sources, with their Social Security number as the primary key in one source, their phone number in another, and a surrogate in the third.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Yet a data warehouse may require the consolidation of all the customer information into one dimension.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] A recommended way to deal with the concern involves adding a warehouse surrogate key, which is used as a foreign key from the fact table.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Usually, updates occur to a dimension's source data, which must be reflected in the data warehouse.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] If the primary key of the source data is required for reporting, the dimension already contains that piece of information for each row.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] If the source data uses a surrogate key, the warehouse must keep track of it even though it is never used in queries or reports; it is done by creating a lookup table that contains the warehouse surrogate key and the originating key.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] This way, the dimension is not polluted with surrogates from various source systems, while the ability to update is preserved.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] The lookup table is used in different ways depending on the nature of the source data.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] A new dimension row is added with the new state of the source system, while the previous dimension row is updated to reflect it is no longer active and time of deactivation.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] ETL vendors benchmark their record-systems at multiple TB (terabytes) per hour (or ~1 GB per second) using powerful servers with multiple CPUs, multiple hard drives, multiple gigabit-network connections, and much memory.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] In real life, the slowest part of an ETL process usually occurs in the database load phase.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Databases may perform slowly because they have to take care of concurrency, integrity maintenance, and indices.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Still, even using bulk operations, database access is usually the bottleneck in the ETL process.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Whether to do certain operations in the database or outside may involve a trade-off.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] For example, removing duplicates using `distinct` may be slow in the database; thus, it makes sense to do it outside.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] On the other side, if using `distinct` significantly (x100) decreases the number of rows to be extracted, then it makes sense to remove duplications as early as possible in the database before unloading data.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] A common source of problems in ETL is a big number of dependencies among ETL jobs.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] For example, job "B" cannot start while job "A" is not finished.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] One can usually achieve better performance by visualizing all processes on a graph, and trying to reduce the graph making maximum use of parallelism, and making "chains" of consecutive processing as short as possible.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Again, partitioning of big tables and their indices can really help.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Another common issue occurs when the data are spread among several databases, and processing is done in those databases sequentially.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Sometimes database replication may be involved as a method of copying data between databases – it can significantly slow down the whole process.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] This approach allows processing to take maximum advantage of parallelism.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] For example, if you need to load data into two databases, you can run the loads in parallel (instead of loading into the first – and then replicating into the second).
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Sometimes processing must take place sequentially.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] For example, dimensional (reference) data are needed before one can get and validate the rows for main "fact" tables.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Some ETL software implementations include parallel processing.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] This enables a number of methods to improve overall performance of ETL when dealing with large volumes of data.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] All three types of parallelism usually operate combined in a single job or task.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] An additional difficulty comes with making sure that the data being uploaded is relatively consistent.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Because multiple source databases may have different update cycles (some may be updated every few minutes, while others may take days or weeks), an ETL system may be required to hold back certain data until all sources are synchronized.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Likewise, where a warehouse may have to be reconciled to the contents in a source system or with the general ledger, establishing synchronization and reconciliation points becomes necessary.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Data warehousing procedures usually subdivide a big ETL process into smaller pieces running sequentially or in parallel.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] To keep track of data flows, it makes sense to tag each data row with "row_id", and tag each piece of the process with "run_id".
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] In case of a failure, having these IDs help to roll back and rerun the failed piece.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Best practice also calls for *checkpoints*, which are states when certain phases of the process are completed.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Once at a checkpoint, it is a good idea to write everything to disk, clean out some temporary files, log the state, etc.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] An established ETL framework may improve connectivity and scalability.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] A good ETL tool must be able to communicate with the many different relational databases and read the various file formats used throughout an organization.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] ETL tools have started to migrate into enterprise application integration, or even enterprise service bus, systems that now cover much more than just the extraction, transformation, and loading of data.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Many ETL vendors now have data profiling, data quality, and metadata capabilities.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] A common use case for ETL tools include converting CSV files to formats readable by relational databases.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] A typical translation of millions of records is facilitated by ETL tools that enable users to input CSV-like data feeds/files and import them into a database with as little code as possible.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] ETL tools are typically used by a broad range of professionals – from students in computer science looking to quickly import large data sets to database architects in charge of company account management, ETL tools have become a convenient tool that can be relied on to get maximum performance.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] ETL tools in most cases contain a GUI that helps users conveniently transform data, using a visual data mapper, as opposed to writing large programs to parse files and modify data types.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] While ETL tools have traditionally been for developers and IT staff, research firm Gartner wrote that the new trend is to provide these capabilities to business users so they can themselves create connections and data integrations when needed, rather than going to the IT staff.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Gartner refers to these non-technical users as Citizen Integrators.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] In online transaction processing (OLTP) applications, changes from individual OLTP instances are detected and logged into a snapshot, or batch, of updates.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] An ETL instance can be used to periodically collect all of these batches, transform them into a common format, and load them into a data lake or warehouse.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Data virtualization can be used to advance ETL processing.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] The application of data virtualization to ETL allowed solving the most common ETL tasks of data migration and application integration for multiple dispersed data sources.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Virtual ETL operates with the abstracted representation of the objects or entities gathered from the variety of relational, semi-structured, and unstructured data sources.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] ETL tools can leverage object-oriented modeling and work with entities' representations persistently stored in a centrally located hub-and-spoke architecture.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Such a collection that contains representations of the entities or objects gathered from the data sources for ETL processing is called a metadata repository and it can reside in memory or be made persistent.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] By using a persistent metadata repository, ETL tools can transition from one-time projects to persistent middleware, performing data harmonization and data profiling consistently and in near-real time.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Extract, load, transform (ELT) is a variant of ETL where the extracted data is loaded into the target system first.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] The architecture for the analytics pipeline shall also consider where to cleanse and enrich data as well as how to conform dimensions.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Some of the benefits of an ELT process include speed and the ability to more easily handle both unstructured and structured data.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Ralph Kimball and Joe Caserta's book *The Data Warehouse ETL Toolkit*, (Wiley, 2004), which is used as a textbook for courses teaching ETL processes in data warehousing, addressed this issue.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Cloud-based data warehouses like Amazon Redshift, Google BigQuery, Microsoft Azure Synapse Analytics, and Snowflake provide highly scalable computing power.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] This lets businesses forgo preload transformations and replicate raw data into their data warehouses, where it can transform them as needed using SQL.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] After having used ELT, data may be processed further and stored in a data mart.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Most data integration tools skew towards ETL, while ELT is popular in database and data warehouse appliances.
[src:apache-nifi/extract-transform-load] Similarly, it is possible to perform TEL (Transform, Extract, Load) where data is first transformed on a blockchain (as a way of recording changes to data, e.g., token burning) before extracting and loading into another data store.
[src:apache-nifi/message-broker] A **message broker** (also known as an **integration broker** or **interface engine**) is an intermediary computer program module that translates a message from the formal messaging protocol of the sender to the formal messaging protocol of the receiver.
[src:apache-nifi/message-broker] Message brokers are elements in telecommunication or computer networks where software applications communicate by exchanging formally defined messages.
[src:apache-nifi/message-broker] Message brokers are a building block of message-oriented middleware (MOM) but are typically not a replacement for traditional middleware like MOM and remote procedure call (RPC).
[src:apache-nifi/message-broker] A message broker is an architectural pattern for message validation, transformation, and routing.
[src:apache-nifi/message-broker] It mediates communication among applications, minimizing the mutual awareness that applications should have of each other in order to be able to exchange messages, effectively implementing decoupling.
[src:apache-nifi/message-broker] The primary purpose of a broker is to take incoming messages from applications and perform some action on them.
[src:apache-nifi/message-broker] Message brokers can decouple end-points, meet specific non-functional requirements, and facilitate reuse of intermediary functions.
[src:apache-nifi/message-broker] For example, a message broker may be used to manage a workload queue or message queue for multiple receivers, providing reliable storage, guaranteed message delivery and perhaps transaction management.
[src:apache-nifi/message-broker] Message brokers are generally based on one of two fundamental architectures: hub-and-spoke and message bus.
[src:apache-nifi/message-broker] In the first, a central server acts as the mechanism that provides integration services, whereas with the latter, the message broker is a communication backbone or distributed service that acts on the bus.
[src:apache-nifi/message-broker] Additionally, a more scalable multi-hub approach can be used to integrate multiple brokers.
[src:apache-nifi/message-broker] Message brokers that are purpose built to achieve time-bounded communications with end-to-end predictability allow for the development of real-time systems that require execution predictability.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] In computing, a **pipeline**, also known as a **data pipeline**, is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] The elements of a pipeline are often executed in parallel or in time-sliced fashion.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Some amount of buffer storage is often inserted between elements.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Pipelining is a commonly used concept in everyday life.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] For example, in the assembly line of a car factory, each specific task—such as installing the engine, installing the hood, and installing the wheels—is often done by a separate work station.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] The stations carry out their tasks in parallel, each on a different car.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Once a car has had one task performed, it moves to the next station.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Variations in the time needed to complete the tasks can be accommodated by "buffering" (holding one or more cars in a space between the stations) and/or by "stalling" (temporarily halting the upstream stations), until the next station becomes available.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Suppose that assembling one car requires three tasks that take 20, 10, and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Then, if all three tasks were performed by a single station, the factory would output one car every 45 minutes.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] By using a pipeline of three stations, the factory would output the first car in 45 minutes, and then a new one every 20 minutes.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] As this example shows, pipelining does not decrease the latency, that is, the total time for one item to go through the whole system.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] It does however increase the system's throughput, that is, the rate at which new items are processed after the first one.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] In computing, a pipeline or data pipeline is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] If a pipeline consists of idempotent steps, these can be rerun without altering the outcome beyond the initial run.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] This is advantageous in terms of reliability and maintenance.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Since the throughput of a pipeline cannot be better than that of its slowest element, the designer should try to divide the work and resources among the stages so that they all take the same time to complete their tasks.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] In the car assembly example above, if the three tasks took 15 minutes each, instead of 20, 10, and 15 minutes, the latency would still be 45 minutes, but a new car would then be finished every 15 minutes, instead of 20.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Under ideal circumstances, if all processing elements are synchronized and take the same amount of time to process, then each item can be received by each element just as it is released by the previous one, in a single clock cycle.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] That way, the items will flow through the pipeline at a constant speed, like waves in a water channel.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] In such "wave pipelines", no synchronization or buffering is needed between the stages, besides the storage needed for the data items.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] More generally, buffering between the pipeline stages is necessary when the processing times are irregular, or when items may be created or destroyed along the pipeline.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] For example, in a graphics pipeline that processes triangles to be rendered on the screen, an element that checks the visibility of each triangle may discard the triangle if it is invisible, or may output two or more triangular pieces of the element if they are partly hidden.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Buffering is also needed to accommodate irregularities in the rates at which the application feeds items to the first stage and consumes the output of the last one.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] The buffer between two stages may be simply a hardware register with suitable synchronization and signalling logic between the two stages.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] When a stage A stores a data item in the register, it sends a "data available" signal to the next stage B.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Once B has used that data, it responds with a "data received" signal to A.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Stage A halts, waiting for this signal, before storing the next data item into the register.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Stage B halts, waiting for the "data available" signal, if it is ready to process the next item but stage A has not provided it yet.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] If the processing times of an element are variable, the whole pipeline may often have to stop, waiting for that element and all the previous ones to consume the items in their input buffers.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] The frequency of such pipeline stalls can be reduced by providing space for more than one item in the input buffer of that stage.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Such a multiple-item buffer is usually implemented as a first-in, first-out queue.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] The upstream stage may still have to be halted when the queue gets full, but the frequency of those events will decrease as more buffer slots are provided.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Queueing theory can tell the number of buffer slots needed, depending on the variability of the processing times and on the desired performance.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] If some stage takes (or may take) much longer than the others, and cannot be sped up, the designer can provide two or more processing elements to carry out that task in parallel, with a single input buffer and a single output buffer.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] As each element finishes processing its current data item, it delivers it to the common output buffer, and takes the next data item from the common input buffer.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] This concept of "non-linear" or "dynamic" pipeline is exemplified by shops or banks that have two or more cashiers serving clients from a single waiting queue.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] In some applications, the processing of an item Y by a stage A may depend on the results or effect of processing a previous item X by some later stage B of the pipeline.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] In that case, stage A cannot correctly process item Y until item X has cleared stage B.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] This situation occurs very often in instruction pipelines.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] For example, suppose that Y is an arithmetic instruction that reads the contents of a register that was supposed to have been modified by an earlier instruction X.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Let A be the stage that fetches the instruction operands, and B be the stage that writes the result to the specified register.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] If stage A tries to process instruction Y before instruction X reaches stage B, the register may still contain the old value, and the effect of Y would be incorrect.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] In order to handle such conflicts correctly, the pipeline must be provided with extra circuitry or logic that detects them and takes the appropriate action.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Rather than halt while waiting for X to be finished, stage A may guess whether the branch will be taken or not, and fetch the next instruction Y based on that guess.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] If the guess later turns out to be incorrect (hopefully rarely), the system would have to backtrack and resume with the correct choice.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] To be effectively implemented, data pipelines need a CPU scheduling strategy to dispatch work to the available CPU cores, and the usage of data structures on which the pipeline stages will operate on.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] For example, UNIX derivatives may pipeline commands connecting various processes' standard IO, using the pipes implemented by the operating system.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Some operating systems may provide UNIX-like syntax to string several program runs in a pipeline, but implement the latter as simple serial execution, rather than true pipelining—namely, by waiting for each program to finish before starting the next one.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Lower level approaches may rely on the threads provided by the operating system to schedule work on the stages: both thread pool-based implementations or on a one-thread-per-stage are viable, and exist.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Other strategies relying on cooperative multitasking exist, that do not need multiple threads of execution and hence additional CPU cores, such as using a round-robin scheduler with a coroutine-based framework.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] In this context, each stage may be instantiated with its own coroutine, yielding control back to the scheduler after finishing its round task.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] This approach may need careful control over the process' stages to avoid them abuse their time slice.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] A pipelined system typically requires more resources (circuit elements, processing units, computer memory, etc.) than one that executes one batch at a time, because its stages cannot share those resources, and because buffering and additional synchronization logic may be needed between the elements.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Moreover, the transfer of items between separate processing elements may increase the latency, especially for long pipelines.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] The additional complexity cost of pipelining may be considerable if there are dependencies between the processing of different items, especially if a guess-and-backtrack strategy is used to handle them.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Indeed, the cost of implementing that strategy for complex instruction sets has motivated some radical proposals to simplify computer architecture, such as RISC and VLIW.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] Compilers also have been burdened with the task of rearranging the machine instructions so as to improve the performance of instruction pipelines.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] In recent years the demands on applications and their underlying hardware have been significant.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] For example, building pipelines with single node applications that trawl through the data row by row is no longer feasible with the volume and variety of big data.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] However, with the advent of data analytics engines such as Hadoop, or more recently Apache Spark, it's been possible to distribute large datasets across multiple processing nodes, allowing applications to reach heights of efficiency several hundred times greater than was thought possible before.
[src:apache-nifi/pipeline-computing] The effect of this today is that even a mid-level PC using distributed processing in this fashion can handle the building and running of big data pipelines.
